Furthermore, the anticipated coefficient of renewable energy consumption is negligible at the 1% level of significance, suggesting that an increase in renewable energy use by 1% is associated with a decrease in carbon dioxide emission by 1.42%. This shows that China can reduce pollution by expanding sustainable energy use. In addition, a 1% increase in urbanization is associated with a 2.04% increase in CO2 emissions, as shown by the significant and positive long run coefficients of LURB. This proves that increased energy usage, rainforest, and change in land use are all results of urbanization in China’s environmental degradation. In addition, at the 5% probability value, the projected long run coefficients of LIND are positive, showing that an increase of 1% in industrial value addition is associated with a rise of 0.17% in dioxide (CO2) emissions (Table 8) and corresponding in Table 9.Table 8
